body.name: TREBLAB HD-Max - Big Loud Bluetooth Speaker - 60W Stereo, 20H Battery, Powerbank, IPX6 Waterproof, TWS, Portable Speaker with Deep Bass, Wireless Outdoor Speakers w/Type-C Connector & Carrying Strap
features: Big Stereo System Sound Quality - HD-Max is a large loud Bluetooth speaker with bass and features a four-speaker design. The 50W speakers and 3 sound modes can function indoors and outdoors.

Long-lasting Battery & Powerbank - HD-Max is a portable bluetooth speaker with powerbank with pass-through charging and USB Type-C connector. Use the 20H play time and quick charge-time to always stay connected.
Pair Two HD-Max Speakers with Lightning-fast Pairing - TREBLAB HD-Max wireless speakers with Bluetooth can pair with one additional HD-Max to give you a strong connection and surround sound quality.

IPX6 Water-Resistant to Conquer Any Environment - The IPX6 waterproof Bluetooth speaker can withstand anything from the beach to the pool, you can even put in the bathroom while you are in the shower.
Expertly Designed With Unparalleled Build Quality - HD-Max portable speakers Bluetooth wireless are built tough and can stand up to anything, thanks to its superior build materials. 1-Year Warranty.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on July 11, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Battery is dead after 2 years - Edit : Great Customer Service
reviews.reviewText: Liked the speaker a lot. The sound is good for the beach and the golf course. However, after 2 years the battery will show fully charged, but only last about 10-15 minutes. reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on February 6, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Great Value & Good Sound
reviews.reviewText: I bought one just to play background music on my porch whilst I'm enjoying a pleasant afternoon or evening outdoors. But liked it so much I bought another so I'd have full stereo! They are loud enough that at higher volume my neighbours can all enjoy my music with me, and the sound quality is much better than I expected for speakers of this size and price (in my home theatre I have 7.2 surround with two 12-inch subs and Cerwin-Vega VS-12s, so I'm used to top quality sound). They have decent highs and midrange, plus plenty of bass for R&B, Ole Skool, Jazz, and Hip-Hop.They're even good enough that when the DJ didn't show up for a store grand opening last weekend, I ran my favourite '90s and '00s playlist through these speakers for four straight hours and the crowd started calling me DJ Busta Hip 'cause I'm a G (geezer; not gangsta)!

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on April 17, 2021
reviews.reviewTitle: 3.0 out of 5 stars Treblab HD Max, you WILL NOT be sorry!!!
reviews.reviewText: The media could not be loaded. First off, if you’re trying to decide between products, I was very happy with both the Treblab HD77 (smaller) AND the Treblab HD Max! Both off impeccable sound quality, response, and bass. Of course a larger diaphragm means more sound and even more bass, so the HD Max blows its little brother out of the water, hands down. Much better sound and construction quality than other brands; price too. I bought my HD Max for my theater projector actually. The awkwardness of dragging around a sound bar and trying to find appropriate placement within or outside of my house is a pain. With the Bluetooth capability and or 3/8 direct input cable good connecting great sound is a snap. The HD Max is built for travel. It’s also not going to keel over and die when subjected to some light rain, splash from a nearby pool, or a spilled drink. Treblab products are simply built like a tank. And the will play for hours on end on a single charge. Using your phone to play music and you get a call, no problem! You can use the speaker for that too. There really is very little that I can find to complain about Treblab’s speakers. This wouldn’t be an honest review however if I didn’t include a couple of minor issues. My biggest complaint with the HD Max (or HD77 for that matter) is the low power warning that you get when nearing empty. Don’t get me wrong, warnings are good, but not when you’re using power to warn me that it’s going to shut off. You’re just robbing me of rocking out to the last few minutes of the song I was listening to. Not to mention the frequency in which the interruption comes. I think a better option would be using a light system. Example: lit green = full power, yellow = moderate, red = need to recharge. There’s really no reason to audibly tell me I need to charge my Treblab; I’ll know when it dies after all. Lastly, and mind you this is purely a limitation of the technology itself and not Treblab’s fault, I can’t wait until the day that using Bluetooth means no longer sacrificing volume. It’s a story as old as time itself, trying to find the balance between quality and functionality. When you take on the flexibility and convenience of the portability that comes with Bluetooth, you are not going to get the same performance that you would with a corded, uninterrupted, powered version of another audio source of equal measure. That said, Treblab is pretty damn close! Best audio investment I’ve ever made. Bottom line, you will not be sorry!12/04/22 - Okay, now I’m a little sorry.....So I’m not going to bad-mouth Treblab, I still have had predominantly good experiences with them and their products. That being said, my HD Max is now dead after 1.5 years. The warranty is good for 1 year, so in fairness, Treblab has fulfilled their promise. No one assumes a purchase will crap out soon after than time though. Usually they last a few years and the buyer understands that after the warranty expires, if you “break it” it won’t be serviced for free. I hadn’t done anything different, the rubber enclosure has always been kept closed aside from charging, it was never around humidity, water, or dropped. It just stopped charging one day. Sad 😭. So, I’m not asserting that if you buy this product it will happen to you, nor do I know how often it happens in general to this product. Also, the customer service agent was very nice and professional in attempting to help me revive my, now useless, heavy-a$$, paperweight. I have to reduce my initial impression of a 5 star review to a 3 star now. In comparison, my Treblab HD77, although smaller and cheaper, has been chugging along with no problems and purchased 1-2 years before the HD Max, as much more robust and expensive speaker. As always, buyer beware.
